WEBVTT

00:02.697 --> 00:04.364
Previously on Smash.

00:04.439 --> 00:05.876
What happened to the sex?

00:06.063 --> 00:07.030
Tom and I
are not connecting.

00:07.064 --> 00:08.064
It's really that bad?

00:08.064 --> 00:09.699
It's just not you.

00:09.734 --> 00:11.034
♪Ce n'est pas
ma faute♪

00:11.068 --> 00:12.402
I wish I could
get out of this show.

00:12.436 --> 00:13.653
I just quit Bombshell.

00:13.704 --> 00:15.038
You're joking.

00:15.072 --> 00:17.908
Jerry broke down.
Bombshell is finally mine.

00:17.942 --> 00:20.744
- Ivy is free now.
- Whoo!

00:20.778 --> 00:22.379
- Oh, sorry.
- Scott!

00:22.413 --> 00:23.613
Julia.

00:23.631 --> 00:26.550
♪ Tell me what I do
to rewrite this story ♪

00:26.584 --> 00:27.684
That is a terrible idea.

00:27.718 --> 00:28.852
We don't need
to spell out our theme.

00:28.886 --> 00:30.921
You want to go out after this
and get a drink?

00:30.955 --> 00:33.273
And when I direct, I tend
to get focused on something,

00:33.307 --> 00:35.609
or someone.

00:40.698 --> 00:43.600
[Soft piano music]

00:43.634 --> 00:51.508
♪

00:53.000 --> 00:59.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:22.907 --> 01:26.176
Okay, stop there.

01:26.210 --> 01:28.445
That reaction
is still a bit soft.

01:28.479 --> 01:29.746
You just shrugged.

01:29.780 --> 01:31.097
When you realize she's gone,
you're angry.

01:31.132 --> 01:32.199
You've been played.

01:32.233 --> 01:33.366
No, I haven't.

01:33.401 --> 01:34.601
Well, she just
took your music.

01:34.602 --> 01:37.387
It's your life's work.
She used you.

01:37.405 --> 01:40.373
Uh, I have no idea
what she did yet.

01:40.408 --> 01:41.391
I mean,
all I know right now

01:41.425 --> 01:42.859
is that we spent
the night together,

01:42.894 --> 01:44.361
and it was the best night
of my life.

01:44.395 --> 01:46.563
Okay, well, I guess
we see the moment differently.

01:46.597 --> 01:49.533
No, you see it wrong.
No offense.

01:49.567 --> 01:51.401
None taken.

01:51.435 --> 01:53.537
Although I don't like to think
of any idea as "wrong"

01:53.571 --> 01:55.822
on the first day
of rehearsal.

01:55.856 --> 01:58.108
All right, you don't want
to play angry, fine.

01:58.142 --> 02:00.327
But do something.

02:00.361 --> 02:03.563
You shrug up there,
they shrug out here.

02:03.598 --> 02:07.067
All right,
reset from the top, please.

02:07.101 --> 02:10.737
♪ Fade up on a star

02:10.770 --> 02:14.074
♪ with it all
in her sights ♪

02:14.108 --> 02:17.077
♪ all the love
and the lights ♪

02:17.111 --> 02:20.997
♪ that surround her

02:21.032 --> 02:24.501
♪ someday
she'll think twice ♪

02:24.535 --> 02:27.420
♪ of the dues
and the price ♪

02:27.455 --> 02:30.624
♪ she'll have to pay

02:30.675 --> 02:32.626
I forgot
how great she is.

02:32.677 --> 02:35.262
- ♪ But not today
- I didn't.

02:35.296 --> 02:38.265
♪ She'll do all she can
[Cell phone ringing]

02:38.299 --> 02:41.768
♪ For the love of one man

02:41.802 --> 02:43.720
♪ and for millions

02:43.754 --> 02:48.725
♪ who love from afar

02:48.759 --> 02:52.028
♪ I'm what
you've been needing ♪

02:52.063 --> 02:54.781
♪ it's all here
and my heart's pleading ♪

02:54.815 --> 02:59.602
♪ let me
be your star ♪

03:07.878 --> 03:10.497
[Cheers and applause]

03:10.548 --> 03:12.415
[Giggles]

03:12.449 --> 03:13.449
It's sensational.

03:13.467 --> 03:14.947
I hate to leave,
but Agnes is waiting.

03:14.952 --> 03:17.286
- Good luck.
- Thanks.

03:17.305 --> 03:18.505
You left
your ringer on?

03:18.556 --> 03:19.856
I forgot.

03:19.890 --> 03:21.825
It's been a week.
He's not calling back.

03:21.859 --> 03:24.361
Scott was one of my closest
friends in grad school.

03:24.395 --> 03:25.745
I mean, we may have
had a falling out,

03:25.796 --> 03:27.464
but that was 15 years ago.

03:27.498 --> 03:30.099
There's no way he's still
holding on to a grudge.

03:30.117 --> 03:32.452
Grudges don't go away.
They get bigger.

03:32.503 --> 03:34.421
I just don't think
that's what it is.

03:34.472 --> 03:36.489
There must be something
I'm not getting.

03:36.524 --> 03:40.443
Yeah.
The hint.

03:40.461 --> 03:44.197
Everyone, please enjoy
croissants and coffee

03:44.231 --> 03:45.448
from Balthazar.

03:45.483 --> 03:46.416
And then it's...

03:46.450 --> 03:47.367
[Mimics whip cracking]

03:47.418 --> 03:48.418
Back to work.

03:48.419 --> 03:50.337
[Laughter]

03:50.388 --> 03:51.921
You're even better than you were
the first time around.

03:51.955 --> 03:53.690
That's because
I'm not terrified.

03:53.724 --> 03:54.658
You're my director now.

03:54.692 --> 03:57.043
And I'm finally Marilyn.

03:57.078 --> 03:58.628
Oh, by the way,
I had an idea.

03:58.646 --> 04:01.364
I feel like I need a bigger
catch breath before Star,

04:01.399 --> 04:02.532
you know, so I can really
belt at the end.

04:02.566 --> 04:04.668
- What do you think?
- I love it.

04:04.702 --> 04:06.269
Whatever instincts
you have,

04:06.303 --> 04:08.705
I want to hear
about them.

04:08.739 --> 04:10.757
You know,
that goes for everyone.

04:10.791 --> 04:12.575
If you have thoughts
or feelings

04:12.593 --> 04:16.495
about your character
or the text,

04:16.529 --> 04:18.565
come to my house tonight
and share them.

04:18.599 --> 04:20.983
I believe,
unlike some people,

04:21.017 --> 04:22.635
that actors have something
to contribute

04:22.670 --> 04:24.231
apart from just doing
what they're told.

04:24.238 --> 04:25.988
Forget Derek.

04:26.006 --> 04:28.324
This is a whole new Bombshell.

04:28.359 --> 04:29.642
Well, then,
if you don't mind,

04:29.694 --> 04:32.295
I could really use a break
in act two.

04:32.329 --> 04:33.380
I'm in every scene.

04:33.414 --> 04:34.514
And I'm not complaining,

04:34.548 --> 04:37.484
but I could really
use a breather.

04:39.570 --> 04:41.104
I will look
into that.

04:41.138 --> 04:44.207
I want my star to be
as happy as she can be.

04:44.241 --> 04:46.676
Ivy looks amazing here,
doesn't she?

04:46.711 --> 04:48.545
She's got
her mother's face.

04:48.579 --> 04:50.379
And her rack.

04:50.398 --> 04:52.232
Shame she's not as big a draw
as Leigh Conroy.

04:52.266 --> 04:53.716
It'd make my job easier.

04:53.734 --> 04:55.335
Why,
is there a problem?

04:55.369 --> 04:57.237
Tom's name does not
fill the seats

04:57.288 --> 04:58.455
the way Derek Wills' does,

04:58.489 --> 05:00.590
so unless we drum up
some excitement,

05:00.608 --> 05:02.488
you're going to be wandering
around Times Square

05:02.493 --> 05:03.743
in a sandwich board.

05:03.778 --> 05:05.762
- So tell me how to fix it.
- Perception.

05:05.796 --> 05:07.347
The only press
on Bombshell right now

05:07.381 --> 05:08.381
is what a hot mess
it is.

05:08.399 --> 05:09.816
We have to turn
that around.

05:09.850 --> 05:11.618
That was his direct.
Try his cell.

05:11.652 --> 05:13.372
Have you been on the phone
the whole time?

05:13.387 --> 05:14.788
I'm aging here, Sean.

05:14.822 --> 05:16.823
I just hit menopause
while on hold.

05:16.857 --> 05:18.875
How's our story
for the New York Times?

05:18.909 --> 05:20.176
I was told
it was a no-go.

05:20.211 --> 05:21.911
Well, that's impossible.

05:21.946 --> 05:23.913
Richard Francis is the head
of the arts section.

05:23.948 --> 05:25.415
He's a very old friend.

05:25.449 --> 05:26.816
No one is friends
in this business.

05:26.851 --> 05:28.067
He's the one
who passed.

05:28.102 --> 05:30.036
Oh, he had to run
to a meeting?

05:30.070 --> 05:31.121
Leave him a message.

05:31.155 --> 05:34.724
"Screw you.
Love, Agnes."

05:34.759 --> 05:36.559
Sam!

05:36.577 --> 05:38.945
Ivy.

05:38.996 --> 05:40.117
How long
is your break again?

05:40.164 --> 05:41.331
A week.

05:41.365 --> 05:42.499
Sorry, it's going
to be a little crazy

05:42.533 --> 05:43.499
while you're here.

05:43.517 --> 05:44.717
How's it going
up there?

05:44.769 --> 05:45.769
Tom actually listens
to me.

05:45.803 --> 05:47.320
He cares about what
I have to say.

05:47.354 --> 05:49.689
Well, I'm jealous.

05:49.740 --> 05:52.008
About the show, or that
I'm up there working with Tom?

05:52.042 --> 05:54.811
Come on, why don't you
come upstairs and say hi?

05:54.845 --> 05:56.479
I'm sure Tom
would love to see you.

05:56.514 --> 05:58.414
If you remember correctly,
he's the one who ended it.

05:58.449 --> 05:59.849
He practically pushed me
out to tour

05:59.867 --> 06:00.817
with book of mormon.

06:00.835 --> 06:04.671
Well, let me
push you back in.

06:04.722 --> 06:07.807
A weird thing just happened
on my way to the bathroom.

06:07.842 --> 06:09.526
Do I want
to hear this?

06:09.560 --> 06:11.561
Marc thanked me
for the monologue

06:11.595 --> 06:14.397
I'm apparently giving him
in act two.

06:14.431 --> 06:17.066
He's a great actor.
What's a little monologue?

06:17.084 --> 06:20.837
A sentence, which is exactly
what he has right now.

06:20.871 --> 06:23.506
Listen, I know that you
want this to be a democracy...

06:23.540 --> 06:27.143
Ah, ah, ah... I prefer
"an intellectual salon."

06:27.161 --> 06:28.411
Right.

06:28.445 --> 06:32.048
But at the end of the day,
you are the director.

06:32.082 --> 06:34.000
You have
to be a parent.

06:34.034 --> 06:35.819
Set strong boundaries,

06:35.853 --> 06:37.971
or you're going to lose control
of your kids.

06:38.005 --> 06:41.591
That was Derek's style,
and his kids were miserable.

06:41.625 --> 06:42.809
I appreciate
your looking out for me,

06:42.843 --> 06:44.310
but I know
what I'm doing.

06:44.345 --> 06:47.747
For the first time in ages,
everything's coming together.

06:50.500 --> 06:53.853
Sam?

06:57.942 --> 06:59.442
You two looked
pretty comfy up there.

06:59.460 --> 07:00.460
We were acting.

07:00.477 --> 07:02.028
It didn't look
like acting.

07:02.062 --> 07:03.212
He's been
blowing me off all week.

07:03.230 --> 07:04.430
He barely talks
to me offstage.

07:04.448 --> 07:06.499
Will you ask him
what's going on?

07:06.534 --> 07:07.500
Guess who has
the casting list?

07:07.535 --> 07:08.918
Oh, I want to see.

07:08.953 --> 07:10.820
It's so crazy they still
haven't cast the diva.

07:10.838 --> 07:12.672
Love her, love her.
Ooh, love to hate her.

07:12.706 --> 07:14.173
Right?

07:14.225 --> 07:16.926
Wow, these people are actually
coming here to meet Derek.

07:16.944 --> 07:18.094
Why don't you
go in for it?

07:18.128 --> 07:20.229
That role
would be perfect for you.

07:20.247 --> 07:21.831
Derek would never
take me seriously.

07:21.865 --> 07:26.286
Look at who
he's meeting with.

07:26.320 --> 07:29.338
What the hell?

07:32.776 --> 07:35.645
Lea Michele?
Lea Michele?

07:35.679 --> 07:38.281
If you say it one more time,
she magically appears.

07:38.315 --> 07:41.351
Do you understand anything
about this show, huh?

07:41.385 --> 07:43.319
The point is
to come out of nowhere,

07:43.354 --> 07:44.687
take people
by surprise.

07:44.705 --> 07:45.822
You cast a celebrity,

07:45.856 --> 07:48.207
it overshadows everything.

07:48.242 --> 07:50.660
The diva is the biggest
superstar in the world, right?

07:50.694 --> 07:52.495
She's Lady Gaga.
She's Madonna.

07:52.529 --> 07:53.696
And if we cast a real star
to mirror that,

07:53.714 --> 07:56.583
that would be
a big coup, all right?

07:56.634 --> 07:57.867
I know what I'm
doing here, Jimmy.

07:57.902 --> 07:59.469
Just let me
do my job.

07:59.503 --> 08:01.054
Oh, I've let you do a lot of
things that I'm not cool with.

08:01.088 --> 08:02.672
Not this one.

08:02.706 --> 08:05.008
It's my show.

08:05.042 --> 08:06.042
Hit it.

08:06.043 --> 08:07.644
[Upbeat jazz music]

08:07.678 --> 08:09.562
♪ One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, eight ♪

08:09.597 --> 08:11.514
♪ one, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, eight ♪

08:11.548 --> 08:13.049
♪ one, two, three, four, five,
six, seven, eight ♪

08:13.083 --> 08:15.318
♪ one, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, eight ♪

08:15.352 --> 08:16.769
♪ one, two, three, four,
five, six ♪

08:16.804 --> 08:18.605
♪ one, two, three, four, five,
six, seven, eight ♪

08:18.656 --> 08:20.490
♪ one, two, three, four,
five, six ♪

08:20.524 --> 08:21.841
♪ one, two, three, four, five,
six, seven, eight ♪

08:21.875 --> 08:22.915
♪ five, six, seven, eight!

08:26.957 --> 08:30.424
- There's a lot of friction, what they want?
- Is charming, isn't it?

08:30.507 --> 08:31.540
Yeah, he's just a kid.

08:31.558 --> 08:33.259
He challenges authority.

08:33.293 --> 08:35.461
I've worked
with a lot of kids.

08:35.495 --> 08:37.346
I've found listening
to them more effective

08:37.381 --> 08:39.865
than ignoring
what they have to say.

08:39.900 --> 08:43.284
I couldn't ignore that
if I tried.

08:43.303 --> 08:45.571
You're a very big get
for this theater, Derek.

08:45.605 --> 08:46.789
I'm aware of that.

08:46.823 --> 08:49.158
But down here, we expect
our directors and writers

08:49.192 --> 08:52.111
to work together.

08:54.398 --> 08:58.184
Find some common ground.

08:58.235 --> 08:59.168
See you
in a bit.

08:59.202 --> 09:02.054
It's a good list.

09:02.089 --> 09:03.329
People running lines
on a break,

09:03.340 --> 09:05.024
fresh pastries...

09:05.058 --> 09:07.076
This is so not like tour life,
let me tell you.

09:07.110 --> 09:08.243
Well, you look great.

09:08.261 --> 09:09.461
You know,
what's really a shame

09:09.463 --> 09:10.863
is being one of the leads
in the hottest show

09:10.897 --> 09:12.782
on tour right now,

09:12.816 --> 09:13.976
and regretting
taking the job.

09:14.001 --> 09:17.503
If you regret it so much,
why not come back?

09:17.537 --> 09:18.921
No, I wasn't...

09:18.955 --> 09:22.591
I'm sure I could
find a place for you here.

09:22.625 --> 09:23.976
Could you
excuse us a minute?

09:24.027 --> 09:26.779
Yeah.

09:26.813 --> 09:28.614
You can't
offer him a role.

09:28.648 --> 09:31.200
There's nothing left,
besides Gladys.

09:31.234 --> 09:32.768
Even our swings
are hired.

09:32.802 --> 09:34.170
You heard him.
He's not happy.

09:34.204 --> 09:35.437
I can find something.

09:35.455 --> 09:39.625
Not without
losing something.

09:39.659 --> 09:42.244
I miss him.
He should be here.

09:42.279 --> 09:45.731
We're not going
to lose anything, trust me.

09:49.185 --> 09:50.803
I tried
to stop her.

09:50.837 --> 09:53.856
Oh, you can't, Mia.

09:53.890 --> 09:55.991
She hasn't stopped moving
since the '70s.

09:56.025 --> 09:58.661
So your name
came up this morning,

09:58.695 --> 10:00.513
and I said
to my publicist,

10:00.564 --> 10:02.048
"there must be
some sort of mistake,

10:02.082 --> 10:06.368
"because the Richard Francis
I know adores a good story,

10:06.386 --> 10:09.238
he adores good theater,
and he adores me."

10:09.272 --> 10:13.259
The problem is, you don't
have a good story, Eileen.

10:13.293 --> 10:17.063
I am in rehearsal
for the biggest musical

10:17.097 --> 10:18.914
yet to be seen
on Broadway,

10:18.949 --> 10:21.384
one that I am back
in control of.

10:21.418 --> 10:22.334
Yeah, but it's been
done to death

10:22.369 --> 10:23.436
in the gossip columns.

10:23.470 --> 10:25.321
Feuding actresses,
oversexed directors,

10:25.355 --> 10:26.555
divorce, betrayal,

10:26.590 --> 10:28.974
and not right
for the New York Times.

10:29.009 --> 10:31.143
Richard, why don't you
come on down to rehearsal?

10:31.194 --> 10:34.296
You can be the first reporter
to see Bombshell redux.

10:34.331 --> 10:37.266
Perhaps you can even
find a new angle.

10:41.405 --> 10:42.571
Ohh.

10:42.605 --> 10:44.907
Locked in the bedroom
at your own party?

10:44.941 --> 10:46.642
You look like me
at my sweet sixteen.

10:46.676 --> 10:50.413
I'm going through the script,
trying to find a place for Sam.

10:50.447 --> 10:52.848
And you're right.
There's nothing.

10:52.883 --> 10:55.384
At least you tried.

10:55.402 --> 10:58.854
You know what I think
you should do tonight?

10:58.872 --> 11:01.056
Drink champagne. Have
fun with your friends.

11:01.091 --> 11:02.475
You've earned
that much.

11:02.509 --> 11:05.661
And tomorrow, you can tell Sam
that you couldn't make it work.

11:05.695 --> 11:08.547
He'll understand.

11:08.582 --> 11:11.567
Ah, I told you
he'd be in here.

11:11.601 --> 11:13.101
What's going on?

11:13.120 --> 11:15.855
Everyone wants to sing.
Come and play for us.

11:15.889 --> 11:17.573
I'm working.

11:17.607 --> 11:18.641
The man doesn't even
have a drink.

11:18.675 --> 11:20.826
Let's get the man
a drink.

11:20.861 --> 11:23.796
- One drink.
- One drink?

11:28.718 --> 11:32.571
- Uh, that's my shirt.
- No, I think it's mine.

11:32.606 --> 11:33.672
Oh, yeah,
did you, uh,

11:33.707 --> 11:35.341
go to Fort Hamilton
in Brooklyn?

11:35.375 --> 11:36.675
Not technically.

11:36.710 --> 11:39.127
But see the way
the fabric's worn through?

11:39.146 --> 11:40.146
Mm.

11:40.180 --> 11:42.298
The neckline
is stretched out

11:42.332 --> 11:47.369
so it falls off one shoulder
like that?

11:47.387 --> 11:51.023
That makes it a girl's shirt.
Can I have it?

11:51.057 --> 11:56.211
Well, you certainly look better
in it than I do, that's for sure.

11:56.229 --> 12:01.316
Hey, what if Amanda
stole a t-shirt from Jesse

12:01.334 --> 12:02.551
the night
they were together?

12:02.586 --> 12:05.254
And then, later on,
he sees her wearing it

12:05.288 --> 12:06.505
in one of her videos...

12:06.540 --> 12:08.824
- Like she's taunting him.
- Or missing him.

12:08.858 --> 12:10.576
You should tell Derek
about that.

12:10.627 --> 12:11.644
Why don't you?

12:11.678 --> 12:13.345
He doesn't really
seem interested

12:13.380 --> 12:15.014
in anything
I have to say.

12:15.048 --> 12:17.132
To be fair, you're not
really listening to him, either.

12:17.167 --> 12:19.852
You may let him push you
around, but I don't have to.

12:19.886 --> 12:22.421
I don't let him
push me around.

12:22.472 --> 12:23.989
I didn't get him
at first,

12:24.024 --> 12:26.442
but once I clicked
into the way he directs,

12:26.476 --> 12:28.110
we started connecting.

12:28.128 --> 12:29.478
No, no,
I'm pretty sure

12:29.513 --> 12:32.047
his "connection" with you
is special.

12:32.065 --> 12:34.333
What's that
supposed to mean?

12:38.505 --> 12:40.422
I'm keeping
the t-shirt.

12:42.742 --> 12:44.660
What's all this?

12:44.694 --> 12:46.495
I've been looking
through old drafts,

12:46.530 --> 12:48.948
trying to find you
a break in act two.

12:48.999 --> 12:50.198
Hey, I recognize this.

12:50.217 --> 12:52.051
It's not
from Bombshell.

12:52.085 --> 12:53.385
It's from a musical
we were working on

12:53.420 --> 12:56.272
about, uh, Vegas
in the '60s.

12:56.306 --> 12:57.606
I played that
for you, remember?

12:57.640 --> 12:58.591
Of course I do.

12:58.625 --> 12:59.742
Why didn't you
finish it?

12:59.776 --> 13:01.093
Because,
other than that song...

13:01.127 --> 13:03.362
- It blew.
- Hey, I loved it.

13:03.396 --> 13:04.980
Not going to lie,
after I heard it,

13:05.015 --> 13:06.715
I started dusting off
my nat king Cole,

13:06.733 --> 13:09.384
hoping one day
I'd get a chance to perform it.

13:09.402 --> 13:10.402
Did you really?

13:10.420 --> 13:12.654
I did. Really.

13:12.672 --> 13:14.039
[Laughs]

13:14.090 --> 13:17.042
[Bright piano music playing]

13:17.093 --> 13:21.714
♪

13:21.765 --> 13:24.934
♪ 'round and 'round
goes the wheel of love ♪

13:24.968 --> 13:29.221
♪ some say
like Russian roulette ♪

13:29.272 --> 13:32.391
♪ there's a jackpot
I'm dreaming of ♪

13:32.442 --> 13:36.061
♪ I'm ready
to place my bet ♪

13:36.112 --> 13:39.782
♪ no need to beg,
steal, or borrow ♪

13:39.816 --> 13:42.901
♪ the future
is looking bright ♪

13:42.953 --> 13:46.655
Both: ♪ yes, I'm laying odds
on tomorrow ♪

13:46.689 --> 13:50.909
♪ so let's start tomorrow
tonight ♪

13:50.961 --> 13:54.546
♪ can't you feel, baby,
we're in the chips ♪

13:54.581 --> 13:58.367
♪ tomorrow's
our lucky day, yeah ♪

13:58.385 --> 14:01.971
♪ I can feel gold
at our fingertips ♪

14:02.005 --> 14:05.540
♪ we'll prosper
if we parlay, yeah ♪

14:05.558 --> 14:09.345
♪ no time for sadness
and sorrow ♪

14:09.379 --> 14:12.714
♪ together,
we'll fight that fight, yes ♪

14:12.732 --> 14:16.218
All: ♪ I'm laying odds
on tomorrow ♪

14:16.236 --> 14:20.389
♪ so let's start tomorrow
tonight ♪

14:20.407 --> 14:24.109
♪ don't need no clover
or lucky charm ♪

14:24.160 --> 14:27.329
♪ that rabbit can
keep his foot ♪

14:27.364 --> 14:31.533
♪ as long as we're
walking arm in arm ♪

14:31.567 --> 14:32.734
♪ it's aces I feel

14:32.752 --> 14:35.237
all: ♪ so shut up
and deal ♪

14:35.255 --> 14:38.841
♪ I know that we're
on a winning streak ♪

14:38.875 --> 14:42.594
♪ the future can't
come too soon ♪

14:42.629 --> 14:46.248
♪ let's climb together
to reach that peak ♪

14:46.266 --> 14:49.968
♪ then, baby,
we'll shoot the moon ♪

14:50.020 --> 14:53.222
♪ I'm high
as Kilimanjaro ♪

14:53.256 --> 14:57.359
♪ and with you, Jack,
I'm ready for flight, yes ♪

14:57.394 --> 15:00.362
All: ♪ I'm laying odds
on tomorrow ♪

15:00.397 --> 15:03.732
♪ so let's start tomorrow
tonight ♪

15:03.766 --> 15:04.766
Dance break!

15:06.236 --> 15:07.703
Whoo!

15:10.773 --> 15:15.411
♪ As long as we're
walking arm in arm ♪

15:15.445 --> 15:16.962
♪ it's aces I feel

15:16.996 --> 15:19.114
all: ♪ so shut up
and deal ♪

15:19.132 --> 15:23.218
♪ oh, I know that we're
on a winning streak ♪

15:23.253 --> 15:25.620
♪ the future can't
come too soon ♪

15:25.638 --> 15:27.056
All: ♪ can't
come too soon ♪

15:27.090 --> 15:30.342
♪ let's climb together
to reach that peak ♪

15:30.393 --> 15:34.129
♪ then, baby,
we'll shoot the moon ♪

15:34.147 --> 15:37.566
♪ I'm high
as Kilimanjaro ♪

15:37.600 --> 15:41.153
♪ and with you, Jack,
I'm ready for flight ♪

15:41.187 --> 15:45.023
All: ♪ yeah, I'm laying odds
on tomorrow ♪

15:45.075 --> 15:48.944
♪ so let's start tomorrow
tonight ♪

15:48.978 --> 15:54.032
♪ let's start tomorrow

15:54.084 --> 15:57.503
♪ tonight

15:57.537 --> 16:03.459
♪ ooh, whee

16:03.493 --> 16:08.597
[cheers and applause]

16:08.631 --> 16:10.315
Haven't used any of that
in a while.

16:10.350 --> 16:11.784
You still got it.

16:11.786 --> 16:14.403
Thank you.

16:14.437 --> 16:15.871
I've missed this..

16:15.905 --> 16:19.207
That song almost feels
like it could be in Bombshell.

16:19.225 --> 16:21.710
Too bad Nat King Cole
didn't know Marilyn.

16:21.728 --> 16:22.828
He could've.

16:22.862 --> 16:24.897
He was a big supporter
of Kennedy's,

16:24.948 --> 16:26.665
performed a ton
at his rallies.

16:26.699 --> 16:28.834
Maybe we could introduce J.F.K.
at one of them.

16:28.868 --> 16:32.171
Uh, I think how we meet J.F.K.
is... is just fine.

16:32.205 --> 16:33.422
When Marilyn does.

16:33.456 --> 16:35.657
Sam,
what do you think?

16:35.675 --> 16:37.543
Ii mean,
I want to come home,

16:37.594 --> 16:39.661
but you don't have to make
all those changes for me.

16:39.679 --> 16:40.679
Call the mormons.

16:40.713 --> 16:42.214
Tell them
you're not coming back.

16:42.248 --> 16:43.348
I'm getting you back
in the show.

16:43.383 --> 16:46.051
Wait, are you sure?
Can you do that?

16:46.102 --> 16:47.186
I'm the director,
aren't I?

16:47.220 --> 16:48.353
Oh, my God.

16:48.388 --> 16:49.388
[Cheering]

16:49.389 --> 16:53.175
- Thank you so much.
- Thank you, Tom.

16:53.193 --> 16:54.193
Yep.

16:58.598 --> 17:00.707
- Hey, what's going on?
- Hey.

17:01.268 --> 17:03.619
I've just put together
some ideas for the show,

17:03.654 --> 17:06.088
and I think
you're going to like them.

17:06.106 --> 17:07.056
Uh, they're led screens.

17:07.089 --> 17:09.724
They allow for a big range
of photographic sets.

17:09.760 --> 17:11.861
They're from Japan,
very high tech.

17:11.895 --> 17:14.730
That's cool,
but we're low-fi.

17:14.765 --> 17:17.782
I figured we'd have,
you know, actual furniture.

17:17.834 --> 17:20.019
Yeah, well, if you're not going to let
me have a name actor for the diva,

17:20.053 --> 17:21.871
we need to make
a statement somewhere.

17:21.905 --> 17:23.622
How about
with the show itself?

17:23.656 --> 17:24.890
I'm just trying
to get us on the same page.

17:24.925 --> 17:27.083
The more you talk, the
less I feel that we are.

17:27.108 --> 17:28.027
This isn't Broadway.

17:28.060 --> 17:29.511
What do you know
about Broadway?

17:29.529 --> 17:31.681
Well, I know
that you're used to getting

17:31.715 --> 17:33.082
anything you want there

17:33.116 --> 17:34.884
and that last time,

17:34.918 --> 17:36.318
you put so many
bells and whistles

17:36.353 --> 17:37.519
all over everything

17:37.537 --> 17:39.516
that no one noticed the
show had any problems

17:39.542 --> 17:40.531
until it was too late.

17:40.557 --> 17:41.707
Jimmy...

17:41.742 --> 17:42.942
I'm just trying
to open your show up.

17:42.976 --> 17:44.410
All right? That's
what a good director does.

17:44.444 --> 17:46.262
The show doesn't
need opening up.

17:46.296 --> 17:49.098
It needs to be true
to what it is.

17:57.040 --> 17:59.175
Well, this is harder
than I thought.

17:59.209 --> 18:00.976
Maybe I can
make it easier.

18:00.994 --> 18:05.264
What do you think about Ana
auditioning for the diva?

18:05.298 --> 18:06.766
Oh, she's super talented.

18:06.800 --> 18:08.284
You haven't seen half
of what she can do.

18:08.318 --> 18:09.735
And she's already here.

18:09.786 --> 18:11.687
Look, Ana is perfect
as Jesse's sister.

18:11.722 --> 18:13.773
Yeah,
but I just thought...

18:15.826 --> 18:17.209
I just thought
I'd ask.

18:24.568 --> 18:26.502
[Sleepy grunt]

18:30.340 --> 18:31.357
[Knocks]

18:31.408 --> 18:35.661
Hey.
Heard you were looking for me.

18:35.712 --> 18:37.430
Where'd you get those?

18:37.481 --> 18:39.381
Jimmy thought
I should have a look,

18:39.416 --> 18:40.983
see what you're planning.

18:41.001 --> 18:42.885
I'm not sure
this is the right aesthetic

18:42.919 --> 18:43.969
for this show,

18:44.020 --> 18:46.722
or the theater.

18:46.740 --> 18:48.124
I thought you were
looking for size, Scott.

18:48.158 --> 18:49.625
I'm sorry,
I'm a bit confused.

18:49.659 --> 18:50.693
Thematically, yes,

18:50.727 --> 18:52.194
one of the best things
about the show

18:52.229 --> 18:53.562
is the chemistry
between your two leads.

18:53.596 --> 18:55.881
I don't want them overwhelmed
by the staging.

18:55.916 --> 18:57.333
That was me thinking
you wanted

18:57.367 --> 19:01.520
to make a splash
with your first show, Scott.

19:01.555 --> 19:03.289
Blow the town away.

19:03.323 --> 19:05.124
Yeah, but I don't want
to bankrupt the theater

19:05.175 --> 19:06.442
to do it.

19:06.476 --> 19:08.177
Well, I've got five
led screens

19:08.211 --> 19:10.513
arriving this morning.

19:10.547 --> 19:11.947
They're all donated.

19:11.982 --> 19:13.315
Contrary
to popular opinion,

19:13.350 --> 19:15.201
I've got some friends
in this business.

19:15.235 --> 19:17.086
Look, it'll
be a Broadway show

19:17.120 --> 19:18.821
with an off-Broadway budget.

19:18.839 --> 19:20.473
Oh, come on,
at least let me show you

19:20.507 --> 19:24.193
what I'm thinking.

19:24.227 --> 19:26.361
It's a little vague right now, but
picture red, white, and blue...

19:26.379 --> 19:27.746
Where's our Marilyn?

19:27.798 --> 19:30.032
I thought we were doing
Mr. and Mrs. Smith today.

19:30.050 --> 19:32.935
We switched up the schedule
a little bit at the last minute.

19:32.969 --> 19:34.186
Well, no one told me.

19:34.221 --> 19:36.071
I have Richard Francis
from the New York Times

19:36.106 --> 19:38.407
meeting me here
to see Ivy today.

19:38.425 --> 19:39.525
I gave her
the morning off

19:39.559 --> 19:41.644
so we could
play around with something.

19:41.678 --> 19:43.829
There's a potential new number
I want to show you,

19:43.864 --> 19:45.504
something I think
the show's been missing.

19:45.549 --> 19:47.500
I cannot believe
that you would do this

19:47.534 --> 19:48.717
without my approval.

19:48.735 --> 19:52.188
You're going
to love Tom's Bombshell.

19:52.222 --> 19:54.206
It's a much more
elegant take...

19:54.241 --> 19:56.091
Well, you call in Ivy
right now!

19:56.126 --> 19:58.310
- Why don't we wait outside?
- Great idea.

19:58.361 --> 20:00.362
Eileen... Hold on. Not until
I show it to you first.

20:00.396 --> 20:01.831
A disagreement
in front

20:01.865 --> 20:05.067
of the most important
arts editor in town?

20:05.101 --> 20:06.501
Great reboot, guys.

20:06.520 --> 20:08.404
- Richard Francis is here?
- Yes.

20:08.438 --> 20:09.822
Tell him
I'll be right out.

20:09.873 --> 20:12.041
Keep him cool.

20:12.075 --> 20:13.976
Can you please
just look at the song?

20:14.010 --> 20:17.029
The show is about
Marilyn, not J.F.K.

20:17.063 --> 20:18.948
I can't have two songs
about him.

20:18.982 --> 20:20.366
I agree.

20:20.417 --> 20:21.901
And Our little secret
is the one

20:21.935 --> 20:23.802
that's actually
about Marilyn.

20:23.837 --> 20:27.373
You're the director.
You decide.

20:27.407 --> 20:29.542
And this time, maybe you'd like
to clue me in.

20:33.897 --> 20:36.632
We are not losing

20:36.650 --> 20:39.818
the Marilyn - J.F.K. number.

20:39.870 --> 20:43.038
It's relevant to the story
that we're trying to tell.

20:43.072 --> 20:47.693
This one is not.

20:47.744 --> 20:51.030
I know.

20:51.064 --> 20:52.181
[Sighs]

20:52.215 --> 20:54.350
Uhh!

20:54.384 --> 20:55.851
I promised Sam.

20:55.886 --> 20:58.487
That promise
isn't even 12 hours old.

20:58.521 --> 21:01.507
He'll understand.

21:01.541 --> 21:04.577
What about the hat?

21:04.611 --> 21:07.229
Too much Sammy,
not enough nat, right?

21:07.263 --> 21:09.081
You going
to tell him?

21:09.132 --> 21:13.001
Tell me what?

21:13.019 --> 21:14.887
We cannot
put the number in.

21:14.938 --> 21:18.157
That's...
That's not necessarily...

21:18.208 --> 21:19.842
Tom, I just
left my job.

21:19.876 --> 21:21.894
Tom.

21:21.928 --> 21:25.698
I'm thinking.
I'm thinking.

21:25.749 --> 21:29.752
Sam, um, we'll... we'll be back
in a little while.

21:29.786 --> 21:31.453
- Okay...
- Come on, let's go for a walk.

21:31.471 --> 21:35.908
- What?
- Just come on.

21:35.942 --> 21:38.410
I tried, but I think
he needs to hear it from you.

21:38.445 --> 21:40.446
Just show up at the audition.
Show him what you've got.

21:40.497 --> 21:42.230
No, I don't want
to piss off Derek

21:42.248 --> 21:44.383
and risk losing the part
I already have.

21:44.417 --> 21:45.968
You're not asking him
to give you the part,

21:46.002 --> 21:47.503
just a chance.

21:47.537 --> 21:49.037
No.
He already said no.

21:49.055 --> 21:50.222
I don't want
to push it.

21:50.256 --> 21:52.558
He pushes us.

21:52.609 --> 21:55.527
Okay, you'd be amazing.
We both know it.

21:55.562 --> 21:57.746
Come on,
fight for it.

21:57.781 --> 21:58.814
I still think
you have a shot.

21:58.832 --> 21:59.872
You want me
to grow a pair,

21:59.916 --> 22:01.750
how about you?

22:01.785 --> 22:03.953
I'll talk to Derek
if you talk to Jimmy.

22:03.987 --> 22:06.472
You really think
Derek is going to fold?

22:06.506 --> 22:09.191
Scott doesn't want
his bells and whistles, either.

22:09.225 --> 22:11.310
This theater is downtown.
It's not Broadway.

22:11.361 --> 22:12.695
You told Scott
about it?

22:12.729 --> 22:14.163
What choice
did I have?

22:14.197 --> 22:15.948
I'm not going
to let Derek beat me.

22:15.999 --> 22:16.999
"Beat you"?

22:17.000 --> 22:19.368
Why are you
making this so personal?

22:19.386 --> 22:21.503
Is this about Karen?

22:21.521 --> 22:24.490
Oh, my God.
It so is.

22:24.541 --> 22:28.310
Did something happen
between the two of you?

22:28.345 --> 22:30.879
You remember when you thought
Karen and Derek were dating?

22:30.914 --> 22:32.081
Yeah, well,
they weren't.

22:32.115 --> 22:33.915
But he wants them
to be.

22:33.933 --> 22:37.903
He told me last week
to stay away from her.

22:37.937 --> 22:41.740
Are you going to?

22:41.775 --> 22:45.127
- Hey.
- Oh, hey, buddy.

22:45.161 --> 22:47.362
Thanks for showing Scott
my presentation.

22:47.380 --> 22:50.499
Great news, he really
loves the LED screens.

22:50.533 --> 22:54.586
When you're ready, we'll be doing
Voice in a dream, all right?

23:01.861 --> 23:05.745
There's no new story here Eileen.
Producer and director at odds,

23:05.772 --> 23:07.573
the last minute changes...
It's all been said.

23:07.607 --> 23:09.341
Then say it
a new way!

23:09.376 --> 23:10.993
I mean,
I need the press, Richard.

23:11.027 --> 23:13.395
You could talk about how you
got your show back.

23:13.430 --> 23:15.231
Well, that might
be a very interesting story,

23:15.265 --> 23:16.682
but it
involves my daughter,

23:16.700 --> 23:18.834
and I'm not about to drag her
through this.

23:18.869 --> 23:20.769
That's too bad.

23:20.804 --> 23:22.238
Mother and daughter
banding together

23:22.272 --> 23:26.141
to save a show,
people eat that stuff up.

23:26.176 --> 23:29.945
They do, don't they?

23:29.996 --> 23:33.165
Thanks for your help,
Richard, very much.

23:33.199 --> 23:34.483
Where are you going?

23:34.517 --> 23:35.801
Keep your phone on.

23:35.835 --> 23:40.055
I'm going
to get you a new story.

23:40.090 --> 23:42.591
What are we doing
down here?

23:42.642 --> 23:44.193
Are we buying pot?

23:44.227 --> 23:47.012
I haven't done that
in years.

23:47.030 --> 23:49.248
I'm proud of you.

23:49.282 --> 23:51.617
The way you've stepped up
as director,

23:51.651 --> 23:52.851
executing your vision

23:52.886 --> 23:55.738
while making everyone feel
supported and heard,

23:55.772 --> 23:57.439
it's amazing.

23:57.474 --> 23:59.024
But...

23:59.058 --> 24:00.458
But a director needs
to be a leader,

24:00.493 --> 24:02.011
and a leader
makes hard decisions.

24:02.045 --> 24:03.929
And when it comes
to hard decisions,

24:03.964 --> 24:05.114
he's the best.

24:05.148 --> 24:07.116
No, no, no.
They're in the wrong order.

24:07.150 --> 24:08.217
Are you serious?

24:08.251 --> 24:11.237
All right,
back to the top.

24:17.844 --> 24:18.977
Oh, bloody hell!

24:18.995 --> 24:20.980
The files are too big
for the system.

24:21.014 --> 24:22.014
They keep crashing.

24:22.048 --> 24:23.065
This is ridiculous.

24:23.099 --> 24:25.317
It just needs
to get up and running.

24:25.352 --> 24:26.485
We have three weeks
to rehearse.

24:26.503 --> 24:27.452
Do you want
to spend the whole time

24:27.470 --> 24:28.470
rebooting a computer?

24:28.521 --> 24:29.755
What I don't want

24:29.789 --> 24:32.041
is to show some kid
simply walking across the stage

24:32.075 --> 24:33.292
for five minutes.

24:33.326 --> 24:35.627
It's "some kid"
walking across a stage

24:35.645 --> 24:37.296
to tell a girl
that he loves her.

24:37.330 --> 24:40.165
If we can't get an audience
to care about that on its own,

24:40.183 --> 24:42.484
one of us isn't very good
at his job.

24:42.535 --> 24:44.703
So, what, you're saying
I can't direct this show?

24:44.737 --> 24:47.356
No, I'm saying you hide
behind fancy screens

24:47.390 --> 24:49.108
and orchestras
and clothes

24:49.142 --> 24:53.045
because you have nothing else
up your sleeve.

24:53.063 --> 24:54.129
What do you think, Karen?
Do we need any of this?

24:54.164 --> 24:55.614
Oh, don't put her
in the middle.

24:55.648 --> 24:57.249
I didn't.
You did.

24:57.283 --> 24:58.250
Tell him
what you really think.

24:58.284 --> 24:59.902
- Oh, shut up.
- Oh...

25:01.821 --> 25:05.891
It's okay.
Go ahead.

25:05.925 --> 25:08.761
It's...

25:08.795 --> 25:10.713
Not right
for this show.

25:10.747 --> 25:13.682
I'm sorry, Derek.

25:16.469 --> 25:18.854
Pathetic,
the lot of you.

25:23.076 --> 25:26.078
Hope you
enjoyed the show.

25:31.351 --> 25:34.119
Scott?

25:34.137 --> 25:35.854
What are you
doing here?

25:35.889 --> 25:37.556
Well, you haven't been
returning my calls.

25:37.574 --> 25:39.425
I've been busy.

25:39.459 --> 25:42.544
Right.
Of course.

25:42.595 --> 25:45.097
Sorry.

25:45.131 --> 25:48.534
You're not still mad
about my play, are you?

25:48.568 --> 25:49.768
I-I thought maybe,

25:49.786 --> 25:52.705
and then I realized
that it was 15 years ago.

25:52.739 --> 25:55.207
And I'm sure you understood
that anyone in my position

25:55.241 --> 25:56.408
would have done
the same thing, and...

25:56.442 --> 25:58.794
I wouldn't have.

25:58.828 --> 26:00.596
It was Lincoln center.

26:00.630 --> 26:02.648
You were my friend.

26:02.682 --> 26:03.682
My friend
who promised me

26:03.700 --> 26:05.184
I could direct that play
at the vineyard.

26:05.218 --> 26:07.453
They offered me
Mike Nichols.

26:07.487 --> 26:09.021
What should I have done?

26:09.055 --> 26:10.406
You should have
said no.

26:10.457 --> 26:12.458
It launched my career.

26:12.492 --> 26:14.460
And almost ruined mine.

26:14.494 --> 26:16.578
I promised them that play,
and I lost my slot.

26:16.613 --> 26:17.863
I couldn't work
for a year.

26:17.897 --> 26:20.349
And when I could,
it wasn't in New York.

26:20.383 --> 26:22.267
You've had
a spectacular career.

26:22.301 --> 26:25.938
Yeah, and it took me 15 years
to get back here.

26:25.972 --> 26:27.172
So pardon me

26:27.207 --> 26:30.325
if yours isn't the first face
I want to see.

26:37.817 --> 26:39.318
The way you talked
to those actors in there...

26:39.352 --> 26:40.602
Oh, God, seriously?
This now?

26:40.637 --> 26:43.255
It was awesome.

26:43.289 --> 26:47.826
You really don't care
what they think of you, do you?

26:47.861 --> 26:49.261
No.

26:49.295 --> 26:50.996
How do you sleep
at night,

26:51.030 --> 26:55.084
knowing everybody
hates you?

26:55.118 --> 26:57.953
I'm seriously asking.

26:57.987 --> 27:01.873
Well... you realize
that having them respect you

27:01.891 --> 27:04.827
is more important
than having them like you.

27:07.447 --> 27:10.582
It's a lonely business,
Tom.

27:10.600 --> 27:13.569
You can't be friends
with them.

27:16.539 --> 27:17.739
I don't think
that's going to be a problem

27:17.791 --> 27:18.707
for you and Jimmy.

27:18.741 --> 27:21.360
[Laughs]

27:21.394 --> 27:25.647
That one is killing me.

27:25.682 --> 27:27.232
He's 24 years old,

27:27.267 --> 27:29.301
and he's telling me
how to do my job.

27:29.335 --> 27:31.537
[Laughs]

27:31.571 --> 27:32.737
Reminds me of you
at that age.

27:32.755 --> 27:35.774
Shut up.
I was not that bad.

27:35.809 --> 27:37.025
You were worse.

27:37.060 --> 27:39.394
Arrogant, stubborn,

27:39.446 --> 27:42.064
full of huge ideas
that nobody believed in but you.

27:42.098 --> 27:46.184
In the end,
you were right.

27:46.202 --> 27:49.838
Maybe that kid
is the same.

27:49.873 --> 27:52.074
Listen to him.

27:52.125 --> 27:54.126
He's not your enemy.

28:00.083 --> 28:02.534
[Sighs]

28:03.963 --> 28:06.416
Derek is kind of slice ball, isn't he?

28:06.445 --> 28:07.845
I don't get why Karen
hangs around him all the time.

28:08.543 --> 28:10.695
Who should she be
hanging around?

28:10.729 --> 28:11.879
Jimmy?

28:11.913 --> 28:13.881
No.
That is not what I meant.

28:13.915 --> 28:15.116
I didn't think so.

28:15.150 --> 28:17.635
We've all wanted things
we can't have.

28:17.669 --> 28:20.705
The trick is
to learn to let go

28:20.739 --> 28:23.357
and enjoy the things
that you can have.

28:26.144 --> 28:27.478
What's up?

28:29.748 --> 28:33.284
I started out
in theaters like this.

28:33.318 --> 28:37.755
Actually,
they were worse than this.

28:37.789 --> 28:39.540
They were the sort of theaters
where the audience used

28:39.574 --> 28:41.492
to walk across the stage
in the middle of the performance

28:41.510 --> 28:46.047
to go to the toilet.

28:46.098 --> 28:50.034
But I did some
of my best work in them.

28:50.052 --> 28:54.855
I was innovative
'cause I had to be.

28:54.890 --> 28:58.626
You know, I got bigger jobs,
more money, bigger sets.

29:01.897 --> 29:04.715
And yes...

29:04.750 --> 29:08.436
There is a very slim possibility
that you might have a point.

29:11.673 --> 29:14.575
It's been a while since I had
to think outside the box.

29:16.912 --> 29:20.398
Thanks.

29:20.432 --> 29:23.351
So your show's not about
scenery or props or costumes,

29:23.385 --> 29:27.188
so what is it about?

29:27.222 --> 29:31.475
Two people
falling in love...

29:31.493 --> 29:34.295
And what gets in the way
of that.

29:34.329 --> 29:36.497
And what gets in the way
of love is...

29:36.531 --> 29:40.017
Other people.

29:40.052 --> 29:43.671
In my experience,
at least.

29:43.705 --> 29:46.674
Great.

29:46.708 --> 29:49.610
Well, let's
show that, then.

29:49.644 --> 29:52.296
Okay, so we're halfway
through act one.

29:52.330 --> 29:54.965
Jesse has just heard Amanda
singing a song on the radio,

29:54.983 --> 29:59.286
a song that he wrote
that she stole.

29:59.337 --> 30:01.956
But he's not angry.
He wants to see her again.

30:01.990 --> 30:02.990
So he goes after her.

30:02.991 --> 30:05.576
So stage right
is greenpoint,

30:05.610 --> 30:06.610
where Jesse starts out.

30:06.645 --> 30:09.296
Stage left is L.A.,

30:09.331 --> 30:13.117
where Amanda is performing
her first big concert as Nina.

30:13.135 --> 30:16.537
But the journey is tough.

30:16.571 --> 30:20.040
There are many obstacles
in the way.

30:20.092 --> 30:23.411
Obstacles?

30:23.445 --> 30:26.764
Thank you.

30:26.798 --> 30:29.900
Music track, please.

